comment: Hey Joe. Really enjoy the interviews. Thanks. Concerning Johnny Depp and the perception that he's weird... It may not just be a factor of his wealth. Johnny Depp is an artist.(Not all good actors are.) Artists develop the metaphoric side of their brains. As a result, their values evolve. Their POV evolves. And they behave in a way that's less conventional. Often, a young artist will try to pass as conventional. They fear the ridicule of conventional people. But as they age, they worry less about ridicule and feel more comfortable being different, especially if they have enough money to insulate themselves from those who disapprove. Keep up the good work. All best to you and your family.

comment:
I don't understand why people think that the box office for a movie is how money money the studio made from the movie. For starters, movie theaters make half the box office. And movie studios have lots of other things like overheard and advertising that they're paying for outside of production of the movie. 

In other words, if a movie costs 300 million to make, and the box office was 800 million, the result is that the studio just about broke even (unless they can make use of the IP rights going forward).

comment: You gotta understand the basics of film budgeting to understand why that last "Pirates" movie was a failure. They spent $350 million on production and marketing. He said they made $800 million on the movie. Roughly half of that money goes to the movie theaters. So, they really made $400 million. That's a $50-million profit on a franchise that used to rake in hundreds of millions per movie ‚Äî for a studio that's spending several billion dollars a year to make movies. They canned Depp because the next "Pirates" would probably lose money. On top of that, Disney has a slate of movies, some of which are going to lose money, and they need surefire winners, like "Pirates", to cover those losses. If it's not a surefire winner anymore, you have to change things up or move on.

I personally don't like Jonny Depp. Hate his politics. He says stupid shit. But Jonny Depp sat in costume playing the role of Captain Jack Sparrow inside the Pirates of the Caribbean ride at Disney all day surprising people that floated by on a raft to sell the last movie. comment:
Woman hating ugly guys are ssoo entertaining- 

Johnny Depp‚Äôs History of Violence
kyra

2 years ago

There are some advantages to be a middle-aged woman with Asperger‚Äôs syndrome, and one of those is that I lived through the 80s as a teen and remember it. And what I remember is that Johnny Depp was known as a ‚Äòbad boy‚Äô with a ‚Äòtemper‚Äô and a substance abuse problem prone to attacking people.¬†


The people who defend him online, which now tragically includes a woman I had hitherto had nothing but the utmost respect,¬†JK Rowling, seem to have either forgotten or don‚Äôt know that the accusations of domestic abuse and assault against Depp by his ex-wife Amber Heard (which include¬†pictures¬†and¬†video¬†and¬†a restraining order against Depp¬†and¬†a text from his manager¬†admitting it and¬†documents from other court cases¬†involving Depp) are just the latest in a line of charges.

Johnny Depp is very pretty and (like Mel Gibson) seems to be very nice¬†when he‚Äôs sober, but he‚Äôs also prone to getting wasted and hitting people who anger him. In 1989, Depp was arrested for¬†assaulting a hotel security guard¬†in Canada after the guard asked a drunken Depp and his friends to leave the premises. Charges against Deep were dropped after he promised a judge to be a good boy. (This works only if you are white or rich or preferably both.)


Then, in 1994, Depp was arrested again on¬†charges of criminal mischief¬† when he destroyed a hotel room ‚Äì allegedly because he was having a fight with his girlfriend at the time, 20 year old supermodel Kate Moss. He had to pay almost $10,000 in damages, but again he got off. Likewise, in 1999, Depp was¬†arrested¬†for threatening the paparazzi in London. While it is easy to sympathize with a star threatening paparazzi, it still reveals Depp‚Äôs tendency toward violence when he‚Äôs hammered and annoyed.

Incidentally, he was involved with French model Vanessa Pradis at the time, and although¬†Pradis has defended him¬†as a ‚Äúsensitive, loving‚Äù man who never abused her, its obvious he was still capable of attacking OTHER people during their relationship. Bill Cosby didn‚Äôt rape¬†every¬†woman he met ‚Ä¶ it doesn‚Äôt mean he isn‚Äôt a rapist. Moreover, court documents by Depp‚Äôs former management allege ‚Äú[Depp was being] interviewed by public authorities relating to a serious and troubling issue involving his family ‚Ä¶ [Depp] knowingly lied to public authorities in several respects in connection with these matters‚Ä¶ [His actions] marked lack of concern for certain serious family issues.‚Äù So is Pradis lying for her children?



Johnny Depp was physically abusive to Amber Heard. People accuse his ex-wife for¬†his¬†actions by saying she ‚Äòegged him on‚Äô so they can still enjoy the fandom fantasy of who he is. Just like his friends and fans claimed¬†his rages and assaults in the past¬†were ‚Äújust Johnny being Johnny,‚Äù merely the kind of ‚Äúoutbursts they have come to expect on occasion from an actor who can be as otherworldly as the character he played in¬†Edward¬†Scissorhands.‚Äù

Just like people blamed Mel Gibson‚Äôs ex when he hit her, or the alcohol he drank when he called a cop ‚Äúsugar-tits‚Äù. Just like people claim Mia Farrow lied so they can still watch¬†Woody Allen¬†movies in the pleasant denial that he raped his adopted daughter. Just like people have always blamed the victim and given the abuser a pass.


As for me, I won‚Äôt be watching the¬†Fantastic Beasts¬†sequel. I don‚Äôt watch the¬†Pirates of the Caribbean¬†franchise. I don‚Äôt listen to my old Bill Cosby comedy albums or watch his videos. I don‚Äôt watch Woody Allen films, and I am hesitant to watch films with actors who have even worked with him in the last 20 years. (Oscars are so much more important than raped little girls?) I eschew any former favorites with Mel Gibson in them.

I am torn about Miramax films ‚Ä¶ which ones were the result of Harvey Weinstein‚Äôs sexual abuse? I stopped watching¬†How I Met Your Mother, even the reruns, when they had¬†Mike Tyson, a convicted rapist, on the show as a ‚Äògood guy‚Äô. (Which was a good move because the last season was reportedly shit.) I try my best not to collude with or support abusers and rapists.

But what to do about actors or authors whom I otherwise like when they support or collude with rapists and abusers whom they insist are actually ‚Äògood people‚Äô? Do they get a little leeway for having the same delusions about their friends and family that all human beings are capable of? I still love Rowling‚Äôs books; am I hypocritical to do so or would I be throwing the baby out with the bathwater because she defended know abuser Johnny Depp?

Denial is certainly EASIER to live with than the complexity of dealing with the fall-out of sexual and domestic violence. I can see why people prefer denial to facing uncomfortable reality.


Kyra Cornelius Kramer

comment:
Seriously once a franchise goes like 3 plus films, that's *OVERKILL.* 
The rest of the add on films are just quick cash grabs & the content, from the writing & so forth is NEVER as good as the first 2 films, more so the first film especially.
The Pirates of the Caribbean movies got old after the first 3 came out.
It's all the same garbage just regurgitated through a different storyline.
Just like those *ATROCIOUS, GOD AWFUL* Fast & the Furious shitty movies.
The Fast & the Furious films are the *FUCKING WORST* wastes of film making ever!
Hmm???
Let me guess the new spinoff with the characters played by Dwayne Johnson & that English douche bag Jason Statham is, let me guess,...... gunna have more car chase sequences with souped up automobiles that go extremely fast...... & furious perhaps?
That's not at all like the other 20 craptastic Fast & Furious mind numbing, recycled, rehashed, regurgitated, obnoxious, mundane, predictable & dull movies that are all alike!
However, if I had to, if I was gunna waste some time I'd rather sit through yet another Pirates film than sit in a theater & be bombarded & annoyed by the constant sound of revving engines & lame tough guy one liners from a movie franchise that should've died after the first *UNDERWHELMING* debut & entertainment value for the easily amused.
How is it that nobody gets sick of hearing a car speeding in pretty much most of those scenes & to put it simply, to hear cars revving going vroom vroom?
Next Fast & the Furious movie will be titled.....

Fast & the Furious 101
Cars Go Really Fast Vroom Vroom For Dummies!

Starring Celebrity Douche Bag Son of A Bitch.

With a soundtrack featuring craptastic rappers that all sounds alike with repetitive beats looped over & over & over & over & over again & on & on & on & on & on & on again until infinity!

And the masses will pay top dollar to go & see an hour plus of horse shit!

ARE YOU NOT ENTERTAINED?!?!?........

Sadly, the majority will respond yes.

comment:
Great show as usual Mr Rogon, you always have the most interesting of guests and subjects on your shows.
It's very sad to see what's happened to Johnny Depp but this is what can happen when you use a lot of drink and drugs I guess.
I have a lot of respect for his acting abilities but sadly for those in the stratosphere of stardom they tend to be surrounded by people who are not the best at giving out advise and are usually only in it for themselves, Johnny needs to surround himself with a better quality of advisers, he's certainly not helping himself with what he has at the moment but unfortunately he's his own worst enemy.
I quit drinking and using pills about 14 years ago and stopped smoking weed about 5 years ago, for about 20 years I worked in the film animation industry and have seen people burning out after using too many personality enhancers like powders, strong drink and pills but in the world of fame they seem to be part of the course and are very difficult to avoid.
Speaking for myself I was lucky that I met the right person at the right time who helped me to stop using the things that help to destroy people. The worst is probably alcohol but it's a double edged sword because without it I wouldn't have got to where I got to, now I live a quiet life in the countryside and don't indulge in those anymore, I certainly couldn't afford them then or now but at the time they were a lot of fun that's for sure, but it's hard to say ''No''.

comment: People often don't understand how the money in movie works and how much money is needed to break even. In Joes example: If a movie costs 330M you can add maybe 100M to 150M marketing, so we are talking above 400M here. If you hear people say it "makes" 800M, it always means that it made 800M in ticket sales. About half of that keep the cinemas. So the studio would only get 400M of that 800M in sales. So with the marketing costs, we have a loss in this example.

comment:
Production budget was $320 million ($70 million over budget), marketing budget is usually the same amount, so let's say the total cost of movie was $400-500 million. The film made $795 million worldwide at box office and Disney gets about 50% from ticket sales. Their share of ticket sales decreases over the length of time the movie's in cinemas. That's why studios want big opening weekends, because after the first week when the sales drop, so does the percentage of money from ticket sales they get.

So Disney would have made less than $400 million back from the movie. So when they're spending $320-450 million and they're lucky to get $400 million (which would also have taxes to be paid on it also) it's a failure. Pure and simple.

If Gone With the Wind's worldwide box office was adjusted to today's money, it would've made over $7 billion. Can you imagine a movie making $7 billion dollars in cinemas today? That's over 3 and 1/2 times the amount Avengers: Infinity War made this year, and Gone With the Wind didn't have a $450 million budget.

comment:
Let's look at this from the acting perspective.  The franchise ultimately runs it's course from the literary development standpoint.  In other words, nothing really new can be explored that can top the archetypal discoveries in the original trope.  If you grind a plot enough, you get weak plot coffee.


As an actor, reprising a role is tougher than developing and letting run the character originally.  Add to that a weakened story world by over-development of the archtypalities and it's like chipping from the sand trap in performance delivery terms.


It was a recipe for failure in the making before the words for the new script went on paper, but the need to make money overruled the content care context.


This fail was a result in the macro of inauthentic culture for commerce, and at it's roots, simply cannot be creatively improved from so far into the arc.


But hey, nobody really listens to their comedian.  But they should.  


Johnny, don't be down bro.  Come see me in the city by the bay for a pourover coffee.  I gotta new script that will put the wind back in your sails.  Set it up Joe.

comment:
regarding the budget - 330m is astronomically high, and doesn't even include marketing costs. studios only recoup 50% of a movie's domestic gross and a smaller percentage from internationals - the theater keeps 50% to cover expenses of running the movie. add on marketing budget on top, which for a large movie is often 100m or more.
so a film with a 330m production budget and 100m marketing budget needs to make a minimum of 860m with the domestic standard of 50% cut in order to BREAK EVEN!!! 
now, some international regions will give a 50% or close to cut, but many give less. the most important being china. unless you have a deal with the chinese theaters and governemnt in place then your cut is more likely to be 20-25%. 
lets be generous and apply a blanket international cut of 40% (which is high for international). that means that total budget 430m (production and marketing) needs to gross over 1 billion dollars in order to BREAK EVEN.

you can make astronomical amounts of money, but if your budget is still just fucking stupid to start with, then the studio can still easily lose money.

comment:
Joe Rogan, changed dramatically!! You could feel the transition over the last few years. Went from questioning everything, to ignoring the biggest conspiracies, etc. This isn't a judgement, it's observation based. Everyone who's listened for years, knows. He used to be a go-to, open-minded guy for the paranormal and conspiracies, now he's just ugh. I liked when he talked about Terrence McKenna, psilocybin, DMT, etc. 
Also, the way Dubay got treated, is ridiculous. Eddie Bravo too. I want Neil Degrasse Tyson to debate Eric Dubay, shit, put it on pay-per view. I'd definitely pay to see that. I'm not a flat earther, but I find, the rise in popularity of the notion, intriguing. Joe disagrees. Only retards would waste their time. There's a huge audience for this show down. Which Joe had scheduled February 2018 as a show. Eric and Tyson, 1 on 1, live!! But Eric Never received an invite or anything stating he was scheduled. It was shameless promotion  
Omg, it would be a disaster on Tyson's reputation. Eric, believe it or not, is extremely witty, quick and so well versed on everything NASA and space, Neil really can't say anything, Eric is a source of many sound, notions and while many people hate him for his Flatearth/Zionist stuff, he's actually a very interesting human. I'm continuously asking him questions, he's humble and will talk to anyone. Whether or not you believe in anything. Which I'm rather agnostic, down the line. However, there's reason to all of these things. It's fascinating from an objective and subjective standpoint. Neil will never debate Eric Dubay live. 

Joe Rogan, if you read these comments, which i suspect you do, at times. If you stumble across this, do you mind answering a couple questions? I'd surely improve your status, in the alternative underground, with simple answers. 

I used to love the information you brought to the public. You awakened many people or at least started them down the rabbit hole. Then the hole was closed, per se. 
I'm curious. Did someone contact you? Threatened? Surely you couldn't outright say yes, but I'd feel better knowing, the Joe i respected. A humblish dude, with a vast majority of topics and knowledge to explore. With many talents and skillsets. Was pushed into his current agendas.  Plus, Joe's obviously intelligent, but not the smartest when agreeing with the status quo and judging people. (Joe should be above judgemental thinking). 

So, I doubt I'll get my reply, but I promise to be genuine and nonbiased. I'm a cool, level headed, dude. We'd get along great, aside from the vibes I get from you lately. You are a busy man.

comment:
When you say "Oh it made $800 Million and it cost $330 Million to make, making $500 Million isn't enough'.....well, long story short it isn't and it isn't as cut and dry as 'budget was this, box office was this, subtract the former from the latter and that is our profit'

Studios also spend money marketing films, sometimes amounts nearly equal to what they cost in the case of these blockbusters(In the case of very small budget movies it is easy to see the marketing budget exceed the production budget).....and they don't keep 100% of the Box Office Gross.....on average it is more like 55%(that's a rough average)

So if you spend $230M to make a film, and another $200M marketing the film...you are looking at a total investment that is well over $400M dollars. So yeah...when you consider THAT...making under $800M is not a very good thing. There was a time when movies made BANK on DVD, and there was a time where physical toy sales were huge for franchises.

But in recent years....physical media isn't selling as well, and physical toys aren't selling as well. More and more kids are just playing games on their TV or on their phone or tablet for their entertainment. So before, sometimes not-so-amazing box office numbers could be offset by the 'total revenue' of the film across box office, TV, DVD, Blu Ray, Digital Downloads, Toys, Apparel, etc etc

But now there is more and more pressure on films making money in the theater. So if you spend a giant amount on a film, you need to truly be a massive hit at the box office.

Depp was making $70 million per movie as the series progressed. When they were mega profitable it was worth the money....but as soon as that cash cow dried up, they simply aren't willing to pay him such an astronomical figure if they don't see him as worth it.

comment: The problem with fame , is that people arent told NO!  People around them are afraid  to upset the gravy train . What to most people would be seen as rude or self destructive behaviour  isnt picked up on or commented upon ,when it comes to the star of the show . Pretty soon people believe in their own hype . And when you have a vast amount of wealth , and no one to curb your excesses , you get spoilt and bored . No one holds up the mirror , or says " you know what , your acting like a fucking idiot !"  Its a surprisingly short road from being a little rude , to becoming a full blown monster .    .It should be a lesson to anyone who is gifted a life where everything is possible . Having worked around film sets , ive heard the rumours about him smoking  drugs in between scenes . Now everybody is entitled to do what they wish , but in a normal work enviroment , in possibly any other industry , would this behaviour be tolerated ? I think not . Im sure hes had a damn good time , but i also feel we could be witnessing the sharp decline in this mans career and mental health . And that would be a tragedy , that could possibly be avoided with some timely intervention .

comment:
Many people rely on extrinsic valuables (money, big house, nice cars etc) for their enjoyment or pleasure and excuse me for being corny, but it doesn't fill your heart. There seems to be less intrinsic value nowadays (love, care, compassion for others etc). Having all the money in the world and the fame is not what we truly want. This is a big problem with power and then subsequent media influence... I always think of this taking my dear old Nan for example. She doesn't own a computer or smart phone and instead enjoys tending to her flowers and seeing my close family. She lives a happy life because she has so little and values the small things. So when she gets a mere birthday present she is overwhelmed. Another point is that some people have inner traits that prefer a small quiet life away from social expectations. Look at people like Robin Williams and Michael Jackson.. fantastic in the lime light, but wanted to escape in their private lives. 


I know some poeple might jump up and down and say, yeah but, poor people are depressed because the have no money and feel worthless.. well you don't need money to be worth something to someone. Make someones day, do a good deed, help someone. This is the fulfilment we need.  I think having lots money and lots of stuff solves your short term problems, but it makes you feel empty and especially so if you seek gratification via social media nowadays. And sometimes you may not get enough gratification which may lead you to poor mental health. Social media isn't the case for poor Johnny Depp here, but a generalisation.

comment:
I saw him 2 days before these pictures of him were taken and he was far from looking "sickly". He looked healthy, performed phenomenal and had an amazing show with the rest of the band. 
 In a recent interview with the director (or whoever he was) responded on the absence of Jack Sparrow. He never mentioned, hinted or made any facial expressions or body movements that would indicate he was fired. He stated the new movie will be a reboot which in its own way will pay tribute to Jack Sparrow and the Johnnys work the character will be forever honored and Johnny should be proud of that.  Johnny himself, way before any mention of another film even being talked about, said he didn't think he would do another film. 
As for the ranch, I do believe that was a gift he gave his late mother. Is 14 homes a bit extreme? Yes, but so is Depp in real life. Hes a very quiet and shy person who had the money to buy an entire block of homes so he had no neighbors and a private island. I'd do the same if I were an A list celebrity with more money than I ever dreamt of! The media and magazines try to portray him as some type of lunatic when really he's the most laid back person who never intended on being a movie star in the first place!

330 million and 800 million is Hollywood accounting. To cut even, you need double the original numbers usually. Pirates was probably $330 mil production and guessing anywhere from $100-200+ mil for global marketing


Triple return numbers means its a successful movie. Hits tend to be 5 times or higher. I think the original Saw movie was $1.2 mil budget and made over 100 mil back, to give you an idea.

comment: Just to give people a bit of insight when it comes to movie budgets - the $320 million budget does not include the roughly $150 million in advertising that the studio likely spent. Plus, the cinemas take a cut of the profits. So if a movie grosses $830 million the studio doesn't get all of that. Chances are that on a major movie that cost $320 million to make, the break even point is probably somewhere in the $600 million mark. Now the studio still made a couple hundred million - but the ROI was not good - and they took on a lot of risk and capital by making the movie for $320 + advertising
